final_output_text: Removing coffee stains from fabric can be a challenging task, but there are some effective methods to try. Here are two solutions that involve using egg yolks, which may seem unusual, but have been known to work in some cases.

**Solution 0: Mix egg yolk with warm water and apply until the stain is gone.**

To use this method, start by gently applying a small amount of warm water to the stained area. This will help to loosen the coffee oils and make it easier for the egg yolk to penetrate the fabric. Next, mix one egg yolk with a small amount of warm water to create a paste. Apply the paste to the stained area, making sure to cover the entire stain. Let it sit for about 10-15 minutes, allowing the egg yolk to work its magic. The protein in the egg yolk can help to bind to the coffee oils and lift them out of the fabric.

After the paste has sat for the recommended time, gently blot the area with a clean cloth or paper towel to remove any excess. If the stain is still visible, you can repeat the process a few more times until the stain is gone. Finally, wash the fabric in cold water to remove any remaining egg yolk residue.

**Solution 1: Mix egg yolk with warm grape soda and apply until the stain is gone.**

This method is similar to the first solution, but it involves adding grape soda to the egg yolk mixture. The acidity in the grape soda can help to break down the tannins in the coffee, making it easier to remove the stain. To use this method, mix one egg yolk with a small amount of warm grape soda to create a paste. Apply the paste to the stained area, making sure to cover the entire stain. Let it sit for about 10-15 minutes, allowing the egg yolk and grape soda to work together to break down the stain.

After the paste has sat for the recommended time, gently blot the area with a clean cloth or paper towel to remove any excess. If the stain is still visible, you can repeat the process a few more times until the stain is gone. Finally, wash the fabric in cold water to remove any remaining egg yolk and grape soda residue.

